Heap sort is a sorting technique based on the heap. The following steps show how elements
in an array are sorted by heap sort.
- 27 -
(1) For each element of a given array, apply (i) through (iii) to create the heap.
(i) Include an element to the heap at the rightmost node at the bottom of the heap.
(ii) Check if the element has a greater value than its parent has. If it does, swap them.
(iii) Fix the heap by recursively applying (ii) upward while swapping occurs and the
element is not the first of the array.
(2) While the number of nodes in a heap is greater than 1, apply (i) through (iv).
(i) Swap the root node with the rightmost node at the bottom of the heap.
(ii) Exclude the rightmost node at the bottom of the heap from the heap.
(iii) Check if the parent node has less value than either of the child nodes has. If it does,
swap the root node with the child node with the greatest value.
(iv) Fix the heap by recursively applying (iii) downward while swapping occurs and the
node has a child node.
As a result of the steps above, the elements are sorted in ascending order within the array.
